<text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div rend="parallel">
            <p xml:id="KT389-kilavi">talaimakaṉ kuṟṟēvaṉmakaṉāṉ varaivu malinta tōḻi talaimakaṭkuc
                colliyatu. </p>


            <p xml:lang="en">Uttered to HER by the confidante, who rejoiced,
                with HIS servant, about the marriage. </p>
        </div>

        <div rend="parallel">
            <lg xml:id="KT389">
                <l> neykaṉi kuṟumpūḻ kāya māka</l>
                <l> vārputam peṟuka tōḻi yattai</l>
                <l> peruṅka ṉāṭaṉ varainteṉa vavaṉetir</l>
                <l> naṉṟō makaṉē yeṉṟaṉe</l>
                <l> ṉaṉṟē pōlu meṉṟurait tōṉē.</l>


            </lg>

            <lg xml:lang="en">
                <l rend="indent"> Of <note place="foot">What is the function of <term xml:lang="ta">āka</term> here? Something like "consisting of"?</note>
                    curry [and] small quail, melting in ghee,</l>
                <l> he may obtain [his] fill, friend!</l>
                <l rend="indent2"> Since the man from the land of big stones is chosen, <note place="foot">
                        <term xml:lang="ta">varainteṉa</term> : the context of settling a
                    marriage is certainly clear, but we might ask whether the verb <term xml:lang="ta">varai </term> does already have the meaning "to marry"
                    (as is attested unequivocally in NA 390). T.V.G. for one takes it in another
                    way, transitive and slightly elliptical: "the man from a land of big stones
                    has fixed [everything for the marriage]".</note> </l>
                <l> I said to him <note place="foot">
                        <term xml:lang="ta">avaṉ etir </term> is literally "in front of him" or
                    "confronting him", and the nuance of this strongly marked direct object
                    might be the expectation of an answer, which lays weight on his judgement.</note>
                    “is [that] good, son?”</l>
                <l> “It seems good”, he told [me]. <note place="foot">The subject to <term xml:lang="ta">peṟuka</term> is postponed to the end: <term xml:lang="ta">uraittōṉ</term> . The circular structure of the Tamil
                    is here, because of the inserted main sentence, not even representable.</note>
                </l>


            </lg>
        </div>
